Subject: Quick question — D1 batch insert limits?
Message-ID: <d1-question-001@acmecorp.example.com>
Date: Fri, 09 Feb 2024 16:00:00 -0800
X-Gmail-Labels: Inbox,Work
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8

Hey Josh,

You mentioned you've been working with D1 — do you know what the
batch insert limits are? I need to bulk-load about 50k rows and
wondering if I should chunk it.

Sarah

From josh@acmecorp.example.com Fri Feb 09 16:30:00 2024
From: Josh Baker <josh@acmecorp.example.com>
To: sarah@acmecorp.example.com
Subject: Re: Quick question — D1 batch insert limits?
Message-ID: <d1-question-002@acmecorp.example.com>
In-Reply-To: <d1-question-001@acmecorp.example.com>
References: <d1-question-001@acmecorp.example.com>
Date: Fri, 09 Feb 2024 16:30:00 -0800
X-Gmail-Labels: Sent,Work
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8

Yeah — DB.batch() can handle up to 100 statements per call. Each
statement can be a multi-row INSERT but the total payload needs to
stay under the Worker CPU time limit.

For 50k rows I'd chunk into batches of 50-100 inserts, each inserting
one row. Wrap each batch in DB.batch() for atomicity. That's what I'm
doing for mailstash and it works well.

Josh

